{
  "text": "In the present study changes in sperm quality during storage were not affected by the GnRH analogue utilized. However, in both groups (Control and GnRH) significant changes in motility parameters (except VSL) and percentage of spermatozoa showing high MMP and ATP content were observed throughout 3 days of storage. According to our previous studies [CITATION_1] Wierzcho\u015b-Hilczer 2009, Gogol 2013 ) the most sensitive parameters of semen quality were motility (especially TMOT and PMOT) and ATP content of the spermatozoa. A small (but statistically significant) decrease in the percentage of spermatozoa with high MMP (7.6% in Control and 6.2% in GnRH group) may suggest that this parameter is less suitable for estimating the in vitro quality of stored rabbit spermatozoa. Mitochondrial respiration could not be sufficient to support sperm motility. In a previous study, a prominent role of glycolysis was proposed in rabbit spermatozoa on the basis of the high activities of pyruvate kinase and dynein-ATPase in sperm flagellum [CITATION_2] . The important role of glycolysis was also proposed in mice, in which spermatozoa remain motile also after the addition of reagents capable of uncoupling oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria [CITATION_3] ).",
